Initially start with a tone set that I thought would work (based on sounds). Change active tones by removing and adding nearby. During task I was influenced by which sounds to activate/deactivate based on the colour combinations being displayed - aiming for hue-similar colours to be simultaneously active.

Overall strategy was more aimed at achieving pleasant patterns and combinations of colours on the tool (e.g. quickly turning off a colour after turning it on and seeing it doesn't fit). During use of the tool this time I felt like I played more with a narrative associated to the visual display, especially towards the end where I increased the frequency of lights active at one time, followed by an 'ending' which had less and less lights active as the piece was ending.

I was aiming for finding pleasant melodies/harmonic movement by individual tones on and off together. I was not focusing on colour matching tones but instead relied on a mixture of trial and error and expectations of what tones would match based on music theory/harmony knowledge.

a differnet game - brain shift not seeing any visuals - but didnt take long to adapt and get into the sounds world. as soon as the visuals wernt there i really did notice a shift in my engament comapered with audio and visual . really thinking about texture and desity, looping was fundamental, starting wth basic, empty loop, and allowing things to quite slowy become randomised to try and not let go of the loop, keeping it sparse, and then come back to another loop - musical container, some sense of predicatability, how would you make an audience feel safe in this sound - felt like a repetition is how that could be acheived.

felt more at ease in not having an artisitic plan - i also have a phrase in my head - there something like a collaboration working with the instrumennt, more acceptance, a level of curiosity not trying to control it as much, had to remind myself to keep looking at the visuals, but i have mush more of an affinity with sound and that felt obvious to me. found it really fun, noticing my personal preferneces and happy to lean in to them, , feeling like personal voice come through

I aimed to draw from a longer/slower movement to something more frenetic then settle again. There appeared to be a two note combinations that produced scattershot bursts and I wanted to swap in and out of one.

I could see a relationship between s few chords and the visual patterns they made, and hoped to progress through these - vertical lines, down right diagonals, clusters of 5. Some attempt to change the pace in an arc.

Aiming to oscillate between fullnes/complexity and simplicity/sparseness, but by different means - on one side using the life span / rate / neighbourhood rules, on the other side using the effect of harmonies and note availability.
